---
// melatonin in children — CONTEXT page (deferred from Phase 5), safety-forward. NOT a graded remedy
// and NOT a recommendation to give a child melatonin: it's parent/carer safety context that also
// folds into the melatonin remedy page's safety section. No tier badge, no evidence-gate chips.
// Clinician-guidance framing throughout; every specific is cited to a source verified firsthand:
// Lelak 2022 MMWR (accidental-ingestion surge, read), Erland 2017 (label-vs-content range, read),
// Cohen 2023 JAMA (gummies mislabelled + some contained CBD — cited only for what its summary
// supports; the specific percentages weren't readable, so they aren't asserted here).
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    n: 1,
    cite: 'Lelak K, Vohra V, Neuman MI, et al. Pediatric Melatonin Ingestions — United States, 2012–2021. MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep. 2022;71(22):725–729.',
    finding:
      'reported pediatric melatonin ingestions rose 530% over the decade, the large majority unintentional in young children, with a rise in hospitalisations and some intensive-care admissions — the basis for treating melatonin as a medicine to lock away, not a harmless candy.',
    pmid: '35653284',
    doi: '10.15585/mmwr.mm7122a1',
  },
  {
    n: 2,
    cite: 'Erland LAE, Saxena PK. Melatonin Natural Health Products and Supplements: Presence of Serotonin and Significant Variability of Melatonin Content. J Clin Sleep Med. 2017;13(2):275–281.',
    finding:
      'lab analysis of 30 supplements: actual melatonin content ranged from 83% below to 478% above the label, varied up to 465% between lots of the same product, and serotonin was detected in eight products — so the number on the label is not a reliable dose.',
    pmid: '27855744',
    doi: '10.5664/jcsm.6462',
  },
  {
    n: 3,
    cite: 'Cohen PA, Avula B, Wang YH, et al. Quantity of Melatonin and CBD in Melatonin Gummies Sold in the US. JAMA. 2023;329(16):1401–1402.',
    finding:
      'an independent analysis of melatonin gummies sold in the US found the measured melatonin frequently did not match the labelled amount, and that some products marketed as melatonin also contained CBD.',
    pmid: '37097362',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="melatonin for children: safety context for parents | Somnary"
  description="melatonin is a medicine, not a candy: accidental-ingestion cases have surged, supplement doses often don't match the label, and gummies can look like sweets. safety context for parents, and why it's a pediatrician conversation first."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/melatonin-children"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · child safety</p>
      <h1 class="title">melatonin in children<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Melatonin is sold beside the vitamins, often as fruit-flavoured gummies, which makes it easy
        to treat as harmless. For children it deserves more caution than that. This page is safety
        context for parents and carers: not a grade, and not a recommendation to give a child
        melatonin.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="giving melatonin to a child is a decision to make with a pediatrician, not from a wiki. this page explains the specific risks that make it a medical conversation."
    />

    <!-- top safety callout: accidental ingestion (serious) -->
    <section class="callout sev-serious" role="note" aria-label="accidental ingestion hazard">
      <div class="callout-head">
        <span class="sigil" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
        <p class="callout-title">store it like a medicine: accidental ingestion is the biggest risk</p>
      </div>
      <p class="callout-body">
        Reported accidental melatonin ingestions by children <strong>rose 530%</strong> between 2012
        and 2021 in the United States, most of them young children finding it on their own, with a
        rise in hospitalisations.<Fn n={1} /> Flavoured gummies that look and taste like sweets are
        part of why. Keep melatonin capped, out of reach, and out of sight, the same as any other
        medicine.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- section 01: the label doesn't tell you the dose -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">the number on the label often isn't the dose in the bottle</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          A child's dose is small, which makes accuracy matter more. Supplement melatonin is
          poorly standardised. When researchers assayed 30 products, actual melatonin content ranged
          from <strong>83% below to 478% above</strong> the labelled amount, and varied by up to
          <strong>465% between lots of the same product</strong>; some products also contained
          serotonin.<Fn n={2} /> A separate analysis of melatonin <em>gummies</em> specifically found
          the measured amount frequently didn't match the label, and that some products marketed as
          melatonin also contained <strong>CBD</strong>.<Fn n={3} /> So &ldquo;1&nbsp;mg&rdquo; on a
          children's gummy is not a dose you can rely on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 02: talk to a pediatrician first -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">it's a pediatrician conversation first</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Persistent sleep trouble in a child can have causes that melatonin would only mask,
          including behavioural sleep patterns, anxiety, or conditions like sleep apnoea. Major
          pediatric and sleep bodies advise talking to a pediatrician <strong>before</strong> giving
          a child melatonin, and trying <strong>behavioural sleep steps first</strong>: a consistent
          bedtime, wind-down routine, and screens off well before bed. A clinician can also weigh the
          things a label can't: your child's age, weight, other conditions, and any medicines they
          take. Melatonin is not a first move, and it is not a nightly default.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 03: if a child has taken too much -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">if a child has swallowed a lot</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          If you think a child has taken more melatonin than intended, don't wait for symptoms to
          decide. Call your poisons information service: in Australia, the
          <strong>Poisons Information Centre on 13 11 26</strong>; in the US,
          <strong>Poison Help on 1-800-222-1222</strong>. Both are free and staffed 24/7. Call your
          local emergency number (<strong>000</strong> in Australia, <strong>911</strong> in the US)
          if the child is drowsy to the point of being hard to wake, having trouble breathing, or
          unresponsive. Elsewhere, contact your national poisons service or emergency number.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={sources} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>

